05428nam a22006855i 9780824860295DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20112011hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248602957 a10.1515/97808248602952doi  a(DE-B1597)484369  a(OCoLC)875239349  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aHD1289.J3b.B769 2011eb 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a333.22221 aBrown, Philip C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCultivating Commons :bJoint Ownership of Arable Land in Early Modern Japan /cPhilip C. Brown. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b21 illus., 12 in color  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Origins and Geopolitical Contexts -- t3. Data and Methodologies -- t4. Varieties and Extent of Joint Landownership -- t5. Lay of the Land: Warichi Practice in Iwade Village -- t6. Warichi and Natural Hazard -- t7. Luck of the Draw? Outcomes and Disputes -- t8. Adaptability, Survivability, and Persistent Influences -- t9. Final Reflections -- tAppendix A: Sources for Redistribution Interval Data and Coordinate Data, Echigo Villages -- tAppendix B: Hikikuji Usage, Supplementary Tables -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCultivating Commons challenges the common understanding of Japanese economic and social history by uncovering diverse landholding practices in early modern Japan. In this first extended treatment of multiple systems of farmland ownership, Philip Brown argues that it was joint landownership of arable land, not virtually private landownership, that characterized a few large areas of Japan in the early modern period and even survived in some places down to the late twentieth century. The practice adapted to changing political and economic circumstances and was compatible with increasing farm involvement in the market. Brown shows that land rights were the product of villages and, to some degree, daimyo policies and not the outcome of hegemons’ and shoguns’ cadastral surveys. Joint ownership exhibited none of the “tragedy of the commons” predicted by much social science theory and in fact explicitly structured a number of practices compatible with longer-term investment in and maintenance of arable land.Exploring early modern society from the ground up, this work provides new perspectives on how villagers organized themselves and their lands, and how their practices were articulated (or were not articulated) to higher layers of administration. It employs an unusually wide array of sources and methodologies: In addition to manuscripts from local archives, it exploits interviews with modern informants who used joint ownership and a combination of modern geographical tools (hazard maps, soil maps, digital elevation models, geographic information systems technologies) to investigate the degree to which the most common form of joint ownership reflected efforts to ameliorate flood and landslide hazard risk as well as microclimate variation. Further it explores the nature of Japanese agricultural practice, its demand on natural resources, and the role of broader environmental factors—all of which infuse the study with new environmental perspectives and approaches.Cultivating Commons will be welcomed by Japanese historians, those in other regional-national fields, and social scientists concerned with issues of resource management, economic development, and rural society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCommonszJapanzNiigata-kenxHistory. 0aFarm tenancyzJapanzNiigata-kenxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asi